 Poverty in Rural India -- tPART III: Practice Reflections and Case Narratives -- tChapter Fourteen. Understand the Brain, Understand Our Children -- tChapter Fifteen. Beyond Deficits: Shifting Perspectives in Child and Youth Mental Health -- tChapter Sixteen. Shifting Identities, Shifting Meanings: Adolescent Siblings and Grief -- tChapter Seventeen. Creating Spaces for Sam: A Story of Healing Trauma Through Narrative Means and Art Therapy -- tChapter Eighteen. Stories of Youth and Family Navigating a New Frontier of Social Media -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Narrating Practice with Children and Adolescents, social workers, sociologists, researchers, and helping professionals share engaging and evocative stories of practice that aim to center the young client’s story. Drawing on work with a variety of disadvantaged populations in New York City and around the world, they seek to raise awareness of the diversity of the individual experiences of youth. They make use of a variety of narrative approaches to offer new perspectives on a range of critical health care, mental health, and social issues that shape the lives of children and adolescents.The book considers the narratives we tell about the lives and experiences of children and adolescents and proposes counternarratives that challenge dominant ideas about childhood. Contributors examine the environments and structures that shape the lives of children and youth from an ecological lens. From their stories emerge questions about how those working with young clients might respond to a changing landscape: How do we define and construct childhood? How do poverty and inequality impact children’s health and welfare? How is childhood lived at the intersection of race, class, and gender? How can practitioners engage children and adolescents through culturally responsive and democratic processes? Offering new frameworks for reflecting on social work practice, the essays in Narrating Practice with Children and Adolescents also serve as a vehicle for exploration of children’s agency and voice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAdolescent psychology. 0aChild psychology. 0aSocial work with children. 0aSocial work with teenagers. 0aStorytelling. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aBaines, Kristina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBesen-Cassino, Yasemin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCaine, Vera, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCourtney, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiaz, Mery F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiaz, Mery, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFernandes, Gretta M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGonzalez, Sabrina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuber, Janice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyatt, Erica Goldblatt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Margot K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnson, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJudd, Rebecca G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMay, Benjamin T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilton, Trevor B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOtero, Jerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalley,